        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink mb-6 dark:text-on-primary">GST Formula Explained</h2>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-6 dark:border-white/15 dark:bg-primary">
          <div class="prose max-w-none text-body dark:text-muted space-y-4">
            <p><strong>GST Exclusive (Adding GST to base price):</strong></p>
            <p>GST Amount = Base Amount × (GST Rate / 100)</p>
            <p>Total Amount = Base Amount + GST Amount</p>
            
            <p><strong>GST Inclusive (Extracting GST from total price):</strong></p>
            <p>Base Amount = Total Amount / (1 + GST Rate / 100)</p>
            <p>GST Amount = Total Amount - Base Amount</p>
            
            <p>For example, if you have a product priced at ₹1,000 excluding GST and GST rate is 18%, the GST amount is ₹180 and total price is ₹1,180. If the selling price including GST is ₹1,180, the base amount is ₹1,000 and GST is ₹180.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-12">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink mb-6 dark:text-on-primary">Common GST Calculation Mistakes</h2>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-6 dark:border-white/15 dark:bg-primary">
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-body dark:text-muted">
            <li><strong>Wrong GST rate:</strong> Applying incorrect GST rates leads to overcharging or undercharging, which can attract penalties. Always verify the applicable rate from the official GST rate list.</li>
            <li><strong>Confusing inclusive and exclusive:</strong> Mixing up GST inclusive and exclusive calculations is a common error. Ensure you know whether the given amount includes GST or not before calculating.</li>
            <li><strong>Not claiming Input Tax Credit:</strong> Businesses often forget to claim ITC on purchases, leading to higher effective tax costs. Maintain proper invoices and file returns timely.</li>
            <li><strong>Wrong HSN/SAC codes:</strong> Using incorrect HSN or SAC codes can result in mismatches and tax disputes. Verify codes from the official GST portal.</li>
            <li><strong>Not separating CGST and SGST:</strong> For intra-state transactions, GST must be split equally between CGST and SGST. IGST is applicable for inter-state transactions.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-12">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink mb-6 dark:text-on-primary">GST Input Tax Credit (ITC)</h2>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-6 dark:border-white/15 dark:bg-primary">
          <div class="prose max-w-none text-body dark:text-muted space-y-4">
            <p>Input Tax Credit is one of the most important features of GST. It allows businesses to claim credit for the GST paid on inputs used in the supply of goods or services. This eliminates the cascading effect of taxes.</p>
            <p>Conditions for claiming ITC:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>You must have a valid GST invoice</li>
              <li>The supplier must have filed their GST returns</li>
              <li>You must have received the goods or services</li>
              <li>You must have filed your GST returns</li>
            </ul>
            <p>ITC cannot be claimed for certain supplies like food and beverages for personal consumption, outdoor catering, and beauty treatment services.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

